Here is the comprehensive, strict command-level audit of the Bazzite Unified Home Server + Gaming Station Guide.

Audit Summary

The provided guide is exceptionally well-architected. It demonstrates advanced, production-grade Linux system administration practices, successfully navigating complex interactions between Fedora Atomic OS (rpm-ostree), SELinux, firewalld, Docker nftables injection, systemd cgroup lifecycles, and Wayland compositor constraints.

The guide relies on deterministic transitions and includes robust fallback mechanisms (e.g., chattr +i for blind mount protection, --collect for systemd unit garbage collection, and precise loginctl parsing). However, a strict audit reveals a few edge-case vulnerabilities, minor dependency assumptions, and potential race conditions that must be addressed to ensure 100% fail-safe execution.

Execution & State Transition Analysis

Phase 1: First Boot & Headless Setup

Action: Masking suspend targets and writing SDDM overrides.

State Check: System transitions from auto-login to a permanent idle TTY/SDDM greeter.

Validation: Correct. Masking sleep targets at the systemd level is the only foolproof way to prevent suspend on a desktop-oriented OS. SDDM's alphabetical parsing guarantees zzz-headless wins.

Phase 3: System Packages

Action: Layering Docker CE and removing podman-docker shim via rpm-ostree.

State Check: Replaces rootless Podman with upstream Docker daemon required for Nextcloud AIO socket orchestration.

Validation: Correct. Note: The installation of fail2ban on Fedora/Bazzite typically requires the fail2ban-firewalld package to properly interface with firewallcmd-rich-rules. Relying solely on the base fail2ban package may cause the jail to fail upon initialization.

Phase 4: Ironclad Security

Action: Changing SSH port, updating SELinux, configuring firewalld, and fail2ban.

State Check: SSH moves to 53222. Port 22 is disabled.

Validation: Executed perfectly in order. Updating the SELinux port label before restarting SSH is a critical dependency correctly identified by the guide.

Phase 6: Data Drive Setup

Action: Formatting, mounting, and labeling the data drive.

State Check: Disk is bound to /srv/nextcloud-data with container_file_t SELinux contexts.

Validation: The use of chattr +i on the unmounted directory is brilliant. It ensures that if the drive fails to mount, Docker will crash with a permission error rather than silently writing to the OS rootfs.

Phase 7 & 10: Docker Services & Networking

Action: Deploying DuckDNS, NPM, and Nextcloud AIO.

State Check: NPM handles external 80/443 traffic (bypassing firewalld via Docker nftables) and routes to Nextcloud internally.

Validation: Binding the Nextcloud Apache container to 127.0.0.1:11000 is highly secure. Routing traffic from NPM to nextcloud-aio-apache via the shared Docker network flawlessly circumvents the localhost restriction on the host machine.

Phase 8: Session Scripts (The Cgroup Escape)

Action: Launching graphical sessions via SSH.

State Check: Temporary SDDM config written, SDDM restarted, and headless state restored.

Validation: The use of systemd-run --collect is masterfully applied. By spawning the cleanup task as a transient system-level service, it successfully escapes the KillUserProcesses=yes SSH session cleanup sequence.

Identified Issues Report
Critical Issues (System-breaking if triggered)

None. The guide successfully avoids all critical execution traps natively.

Major Issues (May introduce instability or unexpected failure)

SDDM Restart Race Condition (Phase 8):

Issue: The session scripts restart SDDM and immediately schedule a headless restoration 5 seconds later (--on-active=5). If the host is under heavy load (e.g., intensive Docker IO), SDDM might take longer than 5 seconds to fully parse the new zz-session-launch.conf and spin up Wayland. If the timer fires and deletes the file before SDDM reads it, the session will fail to launch.

Fix: Increase the transient timer delay to 10 seconds (--on-active=10). This leaves ample time for SDDM initialization without risking the headless default.

Fail2ban Firewalld Integration (Phase 3 & 4):

Issue: In Phase 4, jail.local dictates banaction = firewallcmd-rich-rules. On Fedora-based atomic images, this specific banaction requires the fail2ban-firewalld subpackage, which is not explicitly listed in the Phase 3 rpm-ostree install command. Without it, the jail may fail to ban IPs.

Fix: Update Phase 3 Step 3 to explicitly include fail2ban-firewalld in the package list.

Minor Issues (Efficiency, clarity, or edge-case ergonomics)

Fstab Syntax Validation (Phase 6):

Issue: The guide warns not to skip validation but does not provide a command to verify fstab syntax before rebooting. A malformed fstab (even with nofail) can cause systemd hanging.

Fix: Add sudo findmnt --verify immediately after editing /etc/fstab to validate syntax.

SSH Tunnel KeepAlive (Phase 9 & 10):

Issue: Idle SSH tunnels used for krdp (RDP) or Nginx proxy admin panels will quietly drop after periods of inactivity.

Fix: Add -o ServerAliveInterval=60 to the SSH tunnel commands to keep the connections persistent.

awk Partition Extraction Fragility (Phase 6):

Issue: While lsblk -rn ... | tail -n 1 combined with mkpart wiping the drive is generally safe, it assumes the OS will instantly present the new partition block device sequentially.

Fix: Add sleep 2 between sudo partprobe and the DATA_PART= variable assignment to ensure the kernel has populated /dev/.

Final System State Validation Checklist

To guarantee the system has reached the intended, secure, and fully operational end-state, verify the following observables:

OS Integrity: rpm-ostree status confirms the base image is signed and Docker CE is properly layered without the podman-docker shim.

Network Perimeter: sudo firewall-cmd --list-all shows ONLY port 53222/tcp. Ports 80 and 443 do not appear (managed by Docker nftables), and port 3389 is completely absent.

SELinux State: sudo semanage port -l | grep ssh outputs ssh_port_t tcp 53222.

Storage Mount & Label: ls -Zd /srv/nextcloud-data outputs system_u:object_r:container_file_t:s0.

Fail2ban Active: sudo fail2ban-client status sshd returns an active jail monitoring port 53222.

SDDM Headless Guard: /etc/sddm.conf.d/ contains ONLY zzz-headless-server.conf during system idle.

Docker Routing: curl -sI http://localhost:81 correctly returns a 302 redirect from NPM, proving the Docker network stack is successfully isolating admin panels.

Blind Mount Safety: Unmounting the data drive (sudo umount /srv/nextcloud-data) and attempting to write a file (sudo touch /srv/nextcloud-data/test) returns Operation not permitted due to chattr +i.

